  "texts": [
    "Further, the AI primarily provided alternative, non-conspiratorial explanations and evidence while encouraging critical thinking, rather than attempting to satisfy psychological needs (see SM Section 6).",
    "The durability of our findings across two months, along with the intervention's spillover effects on unrelated conspiracies and behavioral intentions, also suggests that participants seriously considered and internalized the AI's arguments-consistent with the \"central route\" to persuasion (47), which is known to promote durable belief change (and in contrast to the \"peripheral route\" which leverages superficial identity cues or emotional appeals, and produces more ephemeral changes).",
    "Of course, our results do not wholly rule out some role for needs and motivations in the formation and maintenance of conspiracy beliefs, but they do indicate an important (perhaps countervailing, in some cases) role for evidence-based deliberation-especially in challenging and changing these beliefs once they are established.",
    "It is important to note that our goal -refuting existing conspiratorial beliefs -is distinct from other related challenges which have received more attention in the literature.",
    "These include presenting and then debunking pro-conspiracy arguments (48, 49), attempting to increase resistance to conspiracy theories in general (50, 51), and presenting arguments against a specific conspiracy theory to randomly selected crowd workers (52) (53) (54) (55), which have been targeted with modest success by past work (e.g."
